<br>
I don't think any one country or corporate entity would have the guts to go it alone. It's an all or nothing risk - either you make it big if you succeed or lose everything in failure.<br>
<br>
I believe that there are only 2 things that will cause a consortium of corporations/governments to gather the political will to go ahead and build and deploy Orion spacecraft.<br>
<br>
1. continued natural resource/industrial development in the face of increasing pressure from the &quot;greens&quot; will eventually become prohibitively expensive on Earth. Then the economics of developing and expoiting resources in space (ie NEOs or the moon) become realistic. (This of course assumes that the &quot;greens&quot; don't get laws/treaties passed restricting development on the moon! Robinson expored some these concepts in Red/Green/Blue Mars novels)<br>
<br>
2. the real threat of a NEO/astroid/comet impact on Earth. In fact just the knowledge that an impact could happen should be enough of a reason to have a small fleet of Orion like craft ready to go without any further justification. Most of us insure our cars, but never get hit. To me this is the same. At our current level of dependence on technology and global communications in a near global economy, any significant impact on the surface would cause tremendous economic upheaval, not to mention the loss of life and infrastructure. A little insurance to mitigate this potential loss, seems pretty cheap over time - whatever the cost of Orion!<br>
<br>
China could go it alone for pure political posturing reasons, but I think they want into the global economy. Trying to do a surface to orbit Orion unilaterally would likely cost them more than they'd gain. Chinese space stations, missions to the Moon or Mars only serve to increase China's international status, nothing more. For a definitive example look at the Apollo program.<br>
<br>
Anyway that's it<br>
<br>
